\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The age at which an individual starts to reproduce is a key life-history
 trait with profound fitness consequences 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cole1954,Roff1984,Brommer1998,Roff2000,Roff2002,Brommer2002,Krueger2005"

\end_inset

.
 Reproducing early increases the probability of realizing reproduction before
 mortality, while delaying the timing of reproduction allows for the accumulatio
n of more resources, often resulting in a larger fecundity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Blanckenhorn2000"

\end_inset

.
 Consequently, a trade-off between juvenile survival and adult fitness arises,
 suggesting that selection favors an optimal age of sexual maturation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Stearns1992,Roff2002"

\end_inset

.
 However, age at sexual maturition has been shown to have a complicated
 genetic architecture, commonly involving not only genes expressed by the
 offspring itself, but also by genes expressed in the parent or grandparents
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hafer2011,Saastamoinen2013,Kruuk2015"

\end_inset

.
 Moreover, recent studies find that age at maturity is also affected by
 genomic imprinting 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Charalambous2007,Perry2014"

\end_inset

, thus involving differential expression of alleles dependent on their parent
 of origin 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ferguson-Smith2011,Koehler2012"

\end_inset

.
 This raises the question when and where genomic imprinting is expected
 to underly the timing of sexual maturation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although recent theoretical studies have started to assess in which ecological
 and social contexts genomic imprinting is likely to evolve 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "reviewed in"
key "Holman2014,Patten2014,Spencer2014"

\end_inset

, most of these studies focus on an abstract phenotype which only affects
 offspring survival [
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
before "e.g.,"
key "Ubeda2010,Ubeda2011,Ubeda2012,Spencer2006,Spencer2009,Wolf2013"

\end_inset

 but see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Wild2009,Farrell2015,VanCleve2010"

\end_inset

], thus ignoring most of the constraints and trade-offs underlying life-history
 traits in reality.
 To overcome this, here we assess the evolution of genomic imprinting in
 a realistic life-history model on the evolution of age and size at sexual
 maturation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Roff1984,Roff2002,Johnstone2014"

\end_inset

, where faster maturation increases the probability of surviving to maturity
 at the cost of a smaller adult size and thus lower fecundity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We study the evolution of genomic imprinting on age versus size at maturity
 in a structured population, taking a demographically explicit approach
 where local competition and relatedness arise from limited dispersal 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rousset2004,Lion2011,Gardner2010"

\end_inset

.
 Studying a demographical model of age versus size at maturity is essential
 for two key reasons: first, local competition among relatives has been
 repeatedly shown to affect various life-history traits 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pen2000,Ronce2004,Ronce2010,Lion2010a,Kuijper2015a"

\end_inset

, as it changes the trade-off between current and future reproduction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pen2000"

\end_inset

.
 Indeed, in a recent demographical model of age at sexual maturation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Johnstone2014"

\end_inset

, we showed that the sex which experiences more local competition has an
 accelerated rate of sexual maturity.
 Second, relatedness asymmetries due to sex-biased dispersal and/or mating
 skew are well-known to favor the evolution of genomic imprinting 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Haig2000a,Brandvain2010,Brandvain2011,VanCleve2010,Ubeda2010"

\end_inset

.
 This is because sex-biased dispersal leads to asymmetries in relatedness
 between maternally versus paternally inherited alleles and their relatives,
 so that differential gene expression is likely to evolve when the trait
 in question affects interactions between relatives 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Haig2000a"

\end_inset

.
 Consequently, whether genomic imprinting affects age at sexual maturity
 is likely to be strongly dependent on the degree of local competition and
 sex differences in dispersal and/or mating skew.
\end_layout

