\begin_layout Section
The model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our approach is to develop an evolutionary demographic model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hamilton1964a,Taylor1996,Rousset2004,Taylor2007,Lion2011,Lehmann2014"

\end_inset

 of the evolution of genomic imprinting on age at sexual maturation.
 Consider a population distributed over infinitely many territories 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Wright1931,Wright1951"

\end_inset

, in which individuals reproduce sexually and generations are nonoverlapping.
 Each territory contains 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{f}}$
\end_inset

 adult female breeders and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{m}}$
\end_inset

 adult male breeders.
 Territories are linked by juvenile dispersal, so that newborn females (or
 males) disperse to random territory with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

) and remain on their natal patch with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathrm{f}}=1-d_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathrm{m}}=1-d_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similar to seminal models (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Roff1984,Stearns1986"

\end_inset

), we assume that there is a trade-off between survival as an offspring
 and reproductive success as an adult, mediated by age at maturity, which
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 in females and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

 in males.
 Although qualitatively similar, the trade-off takes a slightly different
 form dependent on the sex considered: in adult females, age at maturity
 directly affects the number of offspring produced, while in adult males
 age at maturity determines his fertilization success relative to other
 males.
 Consequently, females provide all investment in offspring, while males
 compete for paternity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will write 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a)$
\end_inset

 for a female's fecundity or a male's relative success in competition for
 paternity, where we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a)$
\end_inset

 increases deceleratingly with 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 At the start of each generation, a focal female of age 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{f}}^{i}$
\end_inset

 then produces a large number of offspring (in a 1:1 sex ratio) proportional
 to her fecundity 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a_{\mathrm{f}}^{i})$
\end_inset

, while the average fecundity in the local patch is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a_{\mathrm{f}})$
\end_inset

.
 A focal male's share of fertilizations of all locally born young is then
 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{f}}/n_{\mathrm{m}}\times f(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{i})/f(a_{\mathrm{m}})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{f}}/n_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

 reflects the average number of matings achieved by a single male, while
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{i})/f(a_{\mathrm{m}})$
\end_inset

 reflects his fertilization success relative to the average fertilization
 success by all males in the local patch.
 Upon birth, female and male offspring survive with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $s(a_{\mathrm{f}})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s(a_{\mathrm{m}})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $s(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 strictly decreases with increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

.
 Female and male offspring who survive to maturity then disperse with respective
 probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

, after which native and immigrant female and male offspring on each patch
 compete for the 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

 breeding positions vacated by the death of the previous generation.
 Offspring who fail to claim a breeding position die, after which the life
 cycle repeats itself.
\end_layout

